         <div type="entry">
                <head>Severos Sebokht</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Severos-Sebokht</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/497</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">488</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="368"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/99</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Scholar, astronomer, philosopher, mathematician, <abbr>bp.</abbr> of
                        Qenneshre (city south of Aleppo); or <abbr>bp.</abbr> of the Monastery of Qenneshre on
                        the east bank of the <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/82">Euphrates</placeName>.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(d. 666/7) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Scholar, astronomer, philosopher, mathematician, <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Bp.</sic>
                                <corr>bp.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> of Qenneshre (city south
                        of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Aleppo">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/18">Aleppo</placeName>
                        </ref>); or <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Bp.</sic>
                                <corr>bp.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> of the <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Qenneshre-Monastery-of">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/230">Monastery
                            of Qenneshre</placeName>
                        </ref> on the east bank of the Euphrates. We do not know
                        much of Severos’s life. Some scholars assume that Severos was born at <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Nisibis">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/142">Nisibis</placeName>
                        </ref>. He became a monk and student in the Monastery of Qenneshre,
                        the famous center of Greek learning founded by <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/John-bar-Aphtonia">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/52">John bar
                            Aphtonia</persName>
                        </ref>. According to the <abbr>Maron.</abbr> Chronicle Severos in his
                        capacity as <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Bp.</sic>
                                <corr>bp.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> came in June 659 to <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Damascus">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/66">Damascus</placeName>
                        </ref> together
                        with <abbr>Bp.</abbr> Theodore to hold a debate on religious matters with the Maronites
                        in the presence of Muʿāwiyya. Several parts of his works survive, although
                        only few have been published to date. Some of Severos’s astronomical works
                        were (partially) published by F. Nau and E. Sachau. The most notable of
                        these are: the ‘Treatise on the Astrolabe’ and the ‘Treatise on the
                        Constellations’. Severos wrote several works concerning the logic of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Aristotle">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/342">Aristotle</persName>
                        </ref>, among which are his ‘Treatise on Syllogisms’ (written
                        in 638) and his Letters to <abbr>Bp.</abbr> Aitalaha of Nineveh and the periodeutes
                        Yawnan. According to the <abbr>ms.</abbr> tradition Severos translated from Middle
                        Persian into Syriac a short exposition of Aristotle’s ‘De interpretatione’,
                        which was composed by <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Pawlos-the-Philosopher">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/675">Pawlos the
                            Philosopher</persName>
                        </ref> (6th <abbr>cent.</abbr>; also known as Pawlos the Persian). Some
                        scholars suggested that Severos translated from Middle Persian into Syriac
                        Pawlos’s compendium on the logic of Aristotle, which was addressed to the
                        Persian shah Khusrau I (for the question of the language in which Pawlos
                        wrote, see Pawlos the Philosopher).</p>
                </div>
